he Hindu caste system, Balinese role-morality, the religious passion of Cortes and Simone Weil, the fate of Colonel Hiromichi Yahara during and after the battle for Okinawa, the ritual human sacrifices of the Aztecs, and the tragedies to which innocence may lead. In doing so, he shakes us out of our deep-seated ways of thinking, enlarging our understanding of the possibilities available to us as we struggle with the problems that stand in the way of how we want to live. The result is a highly interesting journey through time and space that illuminates and helps us cope with some of the most basic predicaments we all face as human beings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aOntology. 0aPhilosophical anthropology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology, history, literature, decision making, predicaments, justice, boredom, ennui, social norms, morality, ethics, sexuality, caste system, class, race, ethnicity, prejudice, discrimination, cortes, simone weil, colonel hiromichi yahara, okinawa, battle, human sacrifice, ritual, rite, religion, spirituality, aztecs, shilluk, hindu, bali, philosophy, ontology, conflict, fate, autonomy, innocence, reflection, good and evil, wrong, sin, righteousness, nonfiction, sociology, michel de montaigne, hypocrisy, authenticity, imperfection.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022635945840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226359595423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226359595/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles